.TH MBR_PATCH 8 "2025" "mbr88 v0.1" "System Administration"
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NAME
.\"
mbr_patch \- view and edit the partition table of an MBR binary image
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SYNOPSIS
.\"
.B mbr_patch
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbr_patch \-p
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbr_patch \-u
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbr_patch \-n
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbr_patch \-h
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\"
.B mbr_patch
reads, displays, and interactively edits the 512-byte Master Boot Record
of an IBM XT-class hard disk image.
It understands the standard four-entry MBR partition table and
the extended boot menu label feature of the
.B mbr88
boot record.
.PP
The program operates in one of four modes selected by a flag on the
command line.
When no flag is given the program runs in read-only view mode.
All modes that write to disk require user confirmation before the file
is touched, and a backup copy is written immediately beforehand.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MODES
.\"
.TP
.B mbr_patch \fImbr_file\fR
.B "View mode (read-only)."
Reads the file, validates it as a 512-byte MBR with a correct
.B 55\ AA
boot signature, prints the partition table, and exits.
If the file does not exist, is not exactly 512 bytes, or lacks the boot
signature, the program prints an error message and exits with a non-zero
status.
This mode is safe to use on any MBR image and never modifies the file.
.TP
.B mbr_patch \-p \fImbr_file\fR
.B "Patch mode."
Validates the file the same way as view mode, then enters an interactive
command session.
The partition table entries can be edited, deleted, and redefined.
If the
.B mbr88
signature is detected and the version is exactly
.BR v0.1 ,
boot menu label editing is also available.
If a higher mbr88 version is detected, a message directs the user to
obtain a newer
.B mbr_patch
from
.IR https://github.com/cpiker/mbr88 .
.TP
.B mbr_patch \-u \fImbr_file\fR
.B "Upgrade mode."
Validates the file, then replaces its boot code with the
.B mbr88 v0.1
boot record while preserving the existing partition table entries.
The file must already exist; use
.B \-n
to create a new image from scratch.
After the upgrade, the interactive command session starts with label
editing enabled and unsaved changes already flagged, so
.B w
will write the new boot code to disk without requiring any further edits.
.TP
.B mbr_patch \-n \fImbr_file\fR
.B "New mode."
Creates a blank
.B mbr88 v0.1
image and enters the interactive command session.
The target file must
.I not
already exist; the program exits with an error if it does.
This prevents accidental overwrites of existing MBR images.
.TP
.B mbr_patch \-h
Print a usage summary and exit.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
.\"
After loading a file in patch, upgrade, or new mode, the program presents
a two-column partition table display and a command prompt.
All changes are made in memory only until explicitly written with
.BR w .
.PP
.TS
l l .
\fBg\fR	Set drive geometry (heads per cylinder, sectors per track).
	Must be run before \fBn\fR.  IBM XT default: 16 heads, 17 sectors.
\fBn\fR	Define a new partition or redefine an existing one.
	Requires geometry to have been set with \fBg\fR first.
	Prompts for starting CHS, ending CHS, partition type, and
	bootable flag.  LBA start and size are computed from the CHS
	values and the current geometry.
\fBd\fR	Delete a partition slot.  Zeros all 16 bytes of the entry
	and its associated boot menu label.
\fBs\fR	Change the partition type byte of an existing entry.
\fBb\fR	Toggle the bootable flag (0x00 / 0x80) on an existing entry.
	See NOTES for mbr88 behaviour regarding this flag.
\fBl\fR	Set the boot menu label for a partition.  Available only on
	mbr88 v0.1 images.  Labels may be up to 11 characters and are
	displayed in the boot menu next to the partition number.
\fBp\fR	Print the current state of the partition table.
\fBt\fR	List common partition type codes.
\fBw\fR	Show the final table, ask for confirmation, write a backup
	copy to \fImbr_file\fB.bak\fR, then write the file.
\fBh\fR	Print the command summary.
\fBq\fR	Quit.  Prompts if there are unsaved changes.
.TE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PARTITION TABLE FORMAT
.\"
The MBR partition table occupies 64 bytes at offset
.B 0x1BE
and holds four 16-byte entries in the IBM CHS format used by the original
PC/XT BIOS.
Each entry contains:
.PP
.TS
l l .
Byte 0	Status: 0x00 = inactive, 0x80 = bootable
Bytes 1\-3	CHS address of the first sector (packed)
Byte 4	Partition type (e.g. 0x01=FAT12, 0x06=FAT16B, 0x83=Linux)
Bytes 5\-7	CHS address of the last sector (packed)
Bytes 8\-11	LBA start sector (32-bit little-endian, computed from CHS)
Bytes 12\-15	LBA sector count (32-bit little-endian, computed from CHS)
.TE
.PP
CHS values should be taken from
.BR fdisk (8)
or the drive's technical specification.
The tool computes LBA start and size automatically from the CHS values
and the drive geometry entered with the
.B g
command.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MBR88 FEATURES
.\"
.B mbr88
is a custom MBR boot record for IBM XT-class hardware that presents an
interactive boot menu and always waits for the user to choose what to boot.
It supports hard disk partitions 1 through 4 and floppy drives A and B.
.PP
The
.B mbr88
boot record is identified by the five-byte ASCII signature
.B mbr88
at MBR offset
.BR 0x1B8 ,
followed by a version byte at
.BR 0x1BD .
The version byte encodes major version in the high nibble and minor version
in the low nibble.
Version
.B 0x01
corresponds to
.BR v0.1 .
.PP
When an
.B mbr88 v0.1
image is loaded in patch mode, four additional 16-byte label slots at
offset
.B 0x41
become editable.
Each slot holds up to 11 characters of ASCII text followed by CR, LF, and
a null terminator.
The boot menu displays the label text next to the corresponding
partition number.
.PP
Future versions of
.B mbr88
may change the label format.
.B mbr_patch
only edits labels on exactly
.B v0.1
images to avoid corrupting a newer format it does not understand.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXAMPLES
.\"
.B Viewing a disk image without modifying it:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbr_patch mbr.bin
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Reading the live MBR from the first hard disk into a file (ELKS / Linux):
.PP
.RS
.nf
dd if=/dev/hda of=mbr.bin bs=512 count=1
mbr_patch mbr.bin
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Reading the MBR under FreeDOS using FDISK:
.PP
.RS
.nf
fdisk /smbr 1
.fi
.RE
This saves the MBR of drive 1 to a file named
.B boot.mbr
in the current directory.
Rename it to
.B mbr.bin
before using it with
.BR mbr_patch .
.PP
.B Upgrading an existing MBR to mbr88, setting labels, and writing:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbr_patch \-u mbr.bin
.fi
.RE
At the prompt, use
.B g
to set geometry,
.B l
to add labels, then
.B w
to write.
.PP
.B Creating a new mbr88 image from scratch:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbr_patch \-n mbr.bin
.fi
.RE
Use
.B g
then
.B n
to define partitions,
.B l
to set labels, then
.B w
to write the file.
.PP
.B Writing the finished image back to disk (ELKS / Linux \(em be careful):
.PP
.RS
.nf
dd if=mbr.bin of=/dev/hda bs=512 count=1
.fi
.RE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NOTES
.\"
.B Bootable flag.
The bootable flag at byte 0 of each partition entry (0x80 = bootable,
0x00 = inactive) is a hint for MBR boot loaders that auto-select the
first marked partition.
.B mbr88
does not use this flag for boot selection \(em it always presents the
full menu and waits for user input.
Any or all partitions may safely be marked bootable when using
.B mbr88
as the boot loader, though other loaders (such as a foreign MBR) may
depend on exactly one partition being marked.
.PP
.B Backup files.
A backup of the original file is written to
.I mbr_file\fB.bak\fR
immediately before any write operation.
The backup is created at confirmation time, not at program startup,
so pressing
.B q
before confirming a write leaves both the original file and the disk
completely untouched.
.PP
.B Drive geometry.
IBM XT hard disks typically use 16 heads per cylinder and 17 sectors
per track.
The geometry must match the values used when the partitions were
originally created.
Incorrect geometry will produce wrong LBA start and size values in the
partition table entries.
When in doubt, use the values reported by
.BR fdisk (8)
for the target drive.
CHS values entered directly from the partition entry bytes do not require
geometry since they are already encoded in CHS form.
.PP
.B Floppy retry.
The
.B mbr88
boot record retries disk reads up to three times before reporting an error.
This is the conventional behaviour for XT-class MBR boot records and
accommodates floppy drives that need time for the motor to reach stable
speed.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH FILES
.\"
.TP
.I mbr_file.bak
Backup of the original file, written immediately before any write
operation completes.
.TP
.I /usr/share/man/man8/mbr_patch.8
This manual page.
.\"
